The paper deals with fundamental problems in distributed computing, specifically Consensus and Broadcast, and their complexity in different communication models. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category. The paper also discusses the use of randomness and error-correcting codes, which are topics related to Information Theory (cs.IT). The study of bio-inspired systems and noisy communication channels suggests that the paper may also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) and Systems and Control (cs.SY) categories. Finally, the paper discusses the applications of Consensus and Broadcast, which may fall under the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) category.
